# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tokenization-data
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The main reason to mask data is to protect information that is classified as personally identifiable information, or mission critical data.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] However, the data must remain usable for the purposes of undertaking valid test cycles.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It must also look real and appear consistent.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It is more common to have masking applied to data that is represented outside of a corporate production system.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] In other words, where data is needed for the purpose of application development, building program extensions and conducting various test cycles.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It is common practice in enterprise computing to take data from the production systems to fill the data component, required for these non-production environments.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] However, this practice is not always restricted to non-production environments.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] In some organizations, data that appears on terminal screens to call center operators may have masking dynamically applied based on user security permissions (e.g. preventing call center operators from viewing credit card numbers in billing systems).
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The primary concern from a corporate governance perspective is that personnel conducting work in these non-production environments are not always security cleared to operate with the information contained in the production data.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This practice represents a security hole where data can be copied by unauthorized personnel, and security measures associated with standard production level controls can be easily bypassed.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This represents an access point for a data security breach.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The data must undergo enough changes so that it is not obvious that the masked data is from a source of production data.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] For example, it may be common knowledge in an organisation that there are 10 senior managers all earning in excess of $300k.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] If a test environment of the organisation's HR System also includes 10 identities in the same earning-bracket, then other information could be pieced together to reverse-engineer a real-life identity.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Theoretically, if the data is obviously masked or obfuscated, then it would be reasonable for someone intending a data breach to assume that they could reverse engineer identity-data if they had some degree of knowledge of the identities in the production data-set.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Accordingly, data obfuscation or masking of a data-set applies in such a manner as to ensure that identity and sensitive data records are protected - not just the individual data elements in discrete fields and tables.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The masked values may be required to be consistent across multiple databases within an organization when the databases each contain the specific data element being masked.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Additional constraints as mentioned in (1) above may also apply depending on the data element(s) involved.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Where different character sets are used across the databases that need to connect in this scenario, a scheme of converting the original values to a common representation will need to be applied, either by the masking algorithm itself or prior to invoking said algorithm.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Substitution is one of the most effective methods of applying data masking and being able to preserve the authentic look and feel of the data records.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It allows the masking to be performed in such a manner that another authentic-looking value can be substituted for the existing value.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] There are several data field types where this approach provides optimal benefit in disguising the overall data subset as to whether or not it is a masked data set.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] For example, if dealing with source data which contains customer records, real life surname or first name can be randomly substituted from a supplied or customised look up file.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] In most cases, the substitution files will need to be fairly extensive so having large substitution datasets as well the ability to apply customized data substitution sets should be a key element of the evaluation criteria for any data masking solution.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The shuffling method is a very common form of data obfuscation.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It is similar to the substitution method but it derives the substitution set from the same column of data that is being masked.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] In very simple terms, the data is randomly shuffled within the column.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] However, if used in isolation, anyone with any knowledge of the original data can then apply a "what if" scenario to the data set and then piece back together a real identity.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The shuffling method is also open to being reversed if the shuffling algorithm can be deciphered.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Data shuffling overcomes reservations about using perturbed or modified confidential data because it retains all the desirable properties of perturbation while performing better than other masking techniques in both data utility and disclosure risk.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Shuffling, however, has some real strengths in certain areas.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] If for instance, the end of year figures for financial information in a test data base, one can mask the names of the suppliers and then shuffle the value of the accounts throughout the masked database.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It is highly unlikely that anyone, even someone with intimate knowledge of the original data could derive a true data record back to its original values.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The numeric variance method is very useful for applying to financial and date driven information fields.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Effectively, a method utilising this manner of masking can still leave a meaningful range in a financial data set such as payroll.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] If the variance applied is around +/- 10% then it is still a very meaningful data set in terms of the ranges of salaries that are paid to the recipients.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The same also applies to the date information.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Encryption is often the most complex approach to solving the data masking problem.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The encryption algorithm often requires that a "key" be applied to view the data based on user rights.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This often sounds like the best solution, but in practice the key may then be given out to personnel without the proper rights to view the data.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This then defeats the purpose of the masking exercise.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Old databases may then get copied with the original credentials of the supplied key and the same uncontrolled problem lives on.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Recently, the problem of encrypting data while preserving the properties of the entities got recognition and a newly acquired interest among the vendors and academia.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] New challenge gave birth to algorithms performing format-preserving encryption.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] These are based on the accepted Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithmic mode recognized by NIST.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Sometimes a very simplistic approach to masking is adopted through applying a null value to a particular field.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The null value approach is really only useful to prevent visibility of the data element.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] In almost all cases, it lessens the degree of data integrity that is maintained in the masked data set.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It is not a realistic value and will then fail any application logic validation that may have been applied in the front end software that is in the system under test.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It also highlights to anyone that wishes to reverse engineer any of the identity data that data masking has been applied to some degree on the data set.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Character scrambling or masking out of certain fields is also another simplistic yet very effective method of preventing sensitive information to be viewed.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It is really an extension of the previous method of nulling out, but there is a greater emphasis on keeping the data real and not fully masked all together.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This is commonly applied to credit card data in production systems.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] For instance, an operator at a call centre might bill an item to a customer's credit card.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] They then quote a billing reference to the card with the last 4 digits of XXXX XXXX xxxx 6789.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] As an operator they can only see the last 4 digits of the card number, but once the billing system passes the customer's details for charging, the full number is revealed to the payment gateway systems.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This system is not very effective for test systems, but it is very useful for the billing scenario detailed above.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] It is also commonly known as a dynamic data masking method.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Additional rules can also be factored into any masking solution regardless of how the masking methods are constructed.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Product agnostic white papers are a good source of information for exploring some of the more common complex requirements for enterprise masking solutions, which include row internal synchronization rules, table internal synchronization rules and table to Table Synchronization Rules.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Data masking is tightly coupled with building test data.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Two major types of data masking are static and on-the-fly data masking.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Static data masking is usually performed on the golden copy of the database, but can also be applied to values in other sources, including files.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Deterministic masking is the process of replacing a value in a column with the same value whether in the same row, the same table, the same database/schema and between instances/servers/database types.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Example: A database has multiple tables, each with a column that has first names.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] With deterministic masking the first name will always be replaced with the same value – “Lynne” will always become “Denise” – wherever “Lynne” may be in the database.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] There are also alternatives to the static data masking that rely on stochastic perturbations of the data that preserve some of the statistical properties of the original data.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Examples of statistical data obfuscation methods include differential privacy and the *DataSifter* method.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] On-the-fly data masking happens in the process of transferring data from environment to environment without data touching the disk on its way.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The same technique is applied to "Dynamic Data Masking" but one record at a time.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This type of data masking is most useful for environments that do continuous deployments as well as for heavily integrated applications.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Organizations that employ continuous deployment or continuous delivery practices do not have the time necessary to create a backup and load it to the golden copy of the database.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Thus, continuously sending smaller subsets (deltas) of masked testing data from production is important.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] In heavily integrated applications, developers get feeds from other production systems at the very onset of development and masking of these feeds is either overlooked and not budgeted until later, making organizations non-compliant.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Having on-the-fly data masking in place becomes essential.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is similar to on-the-fly data masking, but it differs in the sense that on-the-fly data masking is about copying data from one source to another source so that the latter can be shared.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Dynamic data masking happens at runtime, dynamically, and on-demand so that there doesn't need to be a second data source where to store the masked data dynamically.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Dynamic data masking enables several scenarios, many of which revolve around strict privacy regulations e.g. the Singapore Monetary Authority or the Privacy regulations in Europe.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is attribute-based and policy-driven.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Dynamic data masking can also be used to encrypt or decrypt values on the fly especially when using format-preserving encryption.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Several standards have emerged in recent years to implement dynamic data filtering and masking.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] For instance, XACML policies can be used to mask data inside databases.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Network proxy between the application and the database: Captures the SQL and applies rewrite on the select request.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Database proxy: is a variation of network proxy.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Database proxy is deployed usually between applications/users and the database.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Applications and users are connecting to the database through database security proxy.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] There are no changes to the way applications and users are connecting to the database.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] There is also no need of an agent to be installed on the database server.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The sql queries are rewritten, but when implemented, this type of dynamic data masking also supported within store procedures and database functions.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Network proxy between the end-user and the application: identifying text strings and replacing them.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This method is not applicable for complex applications as it will easily cause corruption when the real-time string replacement is unintentionally applied.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Code changes in the applications & XACML: code changes are usually hard to perform, impossible to maintain and not applicable for packaged applications.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Within the application run-time: By instrumenting the application run-time, policies are defined to rewrite the result set returned from the data sources, while having full visibility to the application user.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This method is the only applicable way to dynamically mask complex applications as it enables control to the data request, data result and user result.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Supported by a browser plugin: In the case of SaaS or local web applications, browser add-ons can be configured to mask data fields corresponding to precise CSS Selectors.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] This can either be accomplished by marking sensitive fields in the application, for example by a HTML class or by finding the right selectors that identify the fields to be obfuscated or masked.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] In latest years, organizations develop their new applications in the cloud more and more often, regardless of whether final applications will be hosted in the cloud or on- premises.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] The cloud solutions as of now allow organizations to use infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and software as a service.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] There are various modes of creating test data and moving it from on-premises databases to the cloud, or between different environments within the cloud.
[src:tokenization-data/data-masking] Dynamic Data Masking becomes even more critical in cloud when customers need to protecting PII data while relying on cloud providers to administer their databases.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] In cryptography, **format-preserving encryption** (**FPE**), refers to encrypting in such a way that the output (the ciphertext) is in the same format as the input (the plaintext).
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Typically only finite sets of characters are used; numeric, alphabetic or alphanumeric.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] For such finite domains, and for the purposes of the discussion below, the cipher is equivalent to a permutation of *N* integers {0, ... , *N*−1} where *N* is the size of the domain.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] One motivation for using FPE comes from the problems associated with integrating encryption into existing applications, with well-defined data models.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] A typical example would be a credit card number, such as `1234567812345670` (16 bytes long, digits only).
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Adding encryption to such applications might be challenging if data models are to be changed, as it usually involves changing field length limits or data types.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] For example, output from a typical block cipher would turn credit card number into a hexadecimal (e.g.`0x96a45cbcf9c2a9425cde9e274948cb67`, 34 bytes, hexadecimal digits) or Base64 value (e.g.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] `lqRcvPnCqUJc3p4nSUjLZw==`, 24 bytes, alphanumeric and special characters), which will break any existing applications expecting the credit card number to be a 16-digit number.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Apart from simple formatting problems, using AES-128-CBC, this credit card number might get encrypted to the hexadecimal value `0xde015724b081ea7003de4593d792fd8b695b39e095c98f3a220ff43522a2df02`.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] In addition to the problems caused by creating invalid characters and increasing the size of the data, data encrypted using the CBC mode of an encryption algorithm also changes its value when it is decrypted and encrypted again.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This happens because the random seed value that is used to initialize the encryption algorithm and is included as part of the encrypted value is different for each encryption operation.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Because of this, it is impossible to use data that has been encrypted with the CBC mode as a unique key to identify a row in a database.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] FPE attempts to simplify the transition process by preserving the formatting and length of the original data, allowing a drop-in replacement of plaintext values with their ciphertexts in legacy applications.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Although a truly random permutation is the ideal FPE cipher, for large domains it is infeasible to pre-generate and remember a truly random permutation.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] So the problem of FPE is to generate a pseudorandom permutation from a secret key, in such a way that the computation time for a single value is small (ideally constant, but most importantly smaller than *O(N)*).
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] An *n*-bit block cipher technically *is* a FPE on the set {0, ..., 2*n*-1}.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] If an FPE is needed on one of these standard sized sets (for example, *n* = 64 for DES and *n* = 128 for AES) a block cipher of the right size can be used.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] However, in typical usage, a block cipher is used in a mode of operation that allows it to encrypt arbitrarily long messages, and with an initialization vector as discussed above.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] In this mode, a block cipher is not an FPE.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] In cryptographic literature (see most of the references below), the measure of a "good" FPE is whether an attacker can distinguish the FPE from a truly random permutation.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Various types of attackers are postulated, depending on whether they have access to oracles or known ciphertext/plaintext pairs.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] In most of the approaches listed here, a well-understood block cipher (such as AES) is used as a primitive to take the place of an ideal random function.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This has the advantage that incorporation of a secret key into the algorithm is easy.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Where AES is mentioned in the following discussion, any other good block cipher would work as well.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Implementing FPE with security provably related to that of the underlying block cipher was first undertaken in a paper by cryptographers John Black and Phillip Rogaway, which described three ways to do this.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] They proved that each of these techniques is as secure as the block cipher that is used to construct it.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This means that if the AES algorithm is used to create an FPE algorithm, then the resulting FPE algorithm is as secure as AES because an adversary capable of defeating the FPE algorithm can also defeat the AES algorithm.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Therefore, if AES is secure, then the FPE algorithms constructed from it are also secure.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] In all of the following, *E* denotes the AES encryption operation that is used to construct an FPE algorithm and *F* denotes the FPE encryption operation.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] One simple way to create an FPE algorithm on {0, ..., *N*-1} is to assign a pseudorandom weight to each integer, then sort by weight.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The weights are defined by applying an existing block cipher to each integer.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Black and Rogaway call this technique a "prefix cipher" and showed it was provably as good as the block cipher used.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This method is only useful for small values of *N*.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] For larger values, the size of the lookup table and the required number of encryptions to initialize the table gets too big to be practical.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] If there is a set *M* of allowed values within the domain of a pseudorandom permutation *P* (for example *P* can be a block cipher like AES), an FPE algorithm can be created from the block cipher by repeatedly applying the block cipher until the result is one of the allowed values (within *M*).
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The recursion is guaranteed to terminate.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This has the advantage that the elements of *M* do not have to be mapped to a consecutive sequence {0,...,*N*-1} of integers.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] It has the disadvantage, when *M* is much smaller than *P*'s domain, that too many iterations might be required for each operation.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] If *P* is a block cipher of a fixed size, such as AES, this is a severe restriction on the sizes of *M* for which this method is efficient.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] For example, an application may want to encrypt 100-bit values with AES in a way that creates another 100-bit value.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] With this technique, AES-128-ECB encryption can be applied until it reaches a value which has all of its 28 highest bits set to 0, which will take an average of 228 iterations to happen.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] It is also possible to make a FPE algorithm using a Feistel network.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] A Feistel network needs a source of pseudo-random values for the sub-keys for each round, and the output of the AES algorithm can be used as these pseudo-random values.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] When this is done, the resulting Feistel construction is good if enough rounds are used.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] One way to implement an FPE algorithm using AES and a Feistel network is to use as many bits of AES output as are needed to equal the length of the left or right halves of the Feistel network.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] If a 24-bit value is needed as a sub-key, for example, it is possible to use the lowest 24 bits of the output of AES for this value.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This may not result in the output of the Feistel network preserving the format of the input, but it is possible to iterate the Feistel network in the same way that the cycle-walking technique does to ensure that format can be preserved.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Because it is possible to adjust the size of the inputs to a Feistel network, it is possible to make it very likely that this iteration ends very quickly on average.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] A Thorp shuffle is like an idealized card-shuffle, or equivalently a maximally-unbalanced Feistel cipher where one side is a single bit.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] It is easier to prove security for unbalanced Feistel ciphers than for balanced ones.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] For domain sizes that are a power of two, and an existing block cipher with a smaller block size, a new cipher may be created using VIL mode as described by Bellare, Rogaway.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The Hasty Pudding Cipher uses custom constructions (not depending on existing block ciphers as primitives) to encrypt arbitrary finite small domains.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The FFSEM mode of AES (specification) that has been accepted for consideration by NIST uses the Feistel network construction of Black and Rogaway described above, with AES for the round function, with one slight modification: a single key is used and is tweaked slightly for each round.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] As of February 2010, FFSEM has been superseded by the FFX mode written by Mihir Bellare, Phillip Rogaway, and Terence Spies.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] (specification, **NIST Block Cipher Modes Development*, 2010*).
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] In JPEG 2000 standard, the marker codes (in the range 0xFF90 through 0xFFFF) should not appear in the plaintext and ciphertext.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The simple modular-0xFF90 technique cannot be applied to solve the JPEG 2000 encryption problem.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] For example, the ciphertext words 0x23FF and 0x9832 are valid, but their combination 0x23FF9832 becomes invalid since it introduces the marker code 0xFF98.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Similarly, the simple cycle-walking technique cannot be applied to solve the JPEG2000 encryption problem since two valid ciphertext blocks may give invalid ciphertext when they get combined.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] For example, if the first ciphertext block ends with bytes "...30FF" and the second ciphertext block starts with bytes "9832...", then the marker code "0xFF98" would appear in the ciphertext.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Two mechanisms for format-preserving encryption of JPEG 2000 were given in the paper "Efficient and Secure Encryption Schemes for JPEG2000" by Hongjun Wu and Di Ma.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] To perform format-preserving encryption of JPEG 2000, the technique is to exclude the byte "0xFF" in the encryption and decryption.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Then a JPEG 2000 encryption mechanism performs modulo-n addition with stream cipher; another JPEG 2000 encryption mechanism performs the cycle-walking technique with block cipher.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Several FPE constructs are based on adding the output of a standard cipher, modulo n, to the data to be encrypted, with various methods of unbiasing the result.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The modulo-n addition shared by many of the constructs is the immediately obvious solution to the FPE problem (thus its use in a number of cases), with the main differences being the unbiasing mechanisms used.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This standard was withdrawn on May 19, 2005, so the technique should be considered obsolete in terms of being a formal standard.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The paper "Using Datatype-Preserving Encryption to Enhance Data Warehouse Security" by Michael Brightwell and Harry Smith describes a way to use the DES encryption algorithm in a way that preserves the format of the plaintext.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] This technique doesn't appear to apply an unbiasing step as do the other modulo-n techniques referenced here.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The paper "Format-Preserving Encryption" by Mihir Bellare and Thomas Ristenpart describes using "nearly balanced" Feistel networks to create secure FPE algorithms.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] The paper "Format Controlling Encryption Using Datatype Preserving Encryption" by Ulf Mattsson describes other ways to create FPE algorithms.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] An example of FPE algorithm is FNR (*Flexible Naor and Reingold*).
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] NIST Special Publication 800-38G, "Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation: Methods for Format-Preserving Encryption" specifies two methods: FF1 and FF3.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Details on the proposals submitted for each can be found at the NIST Block Cipher Modes Development site, including patent and test vector information.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Sample values are available for both FF1 and FF3.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Another mode was included in the draft NIST guidance but was removed before final publication.
[src:tokenization-data/format-preserving-encryption] Korea has also developed a FPE standard, FEA-1 and FEA-2.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The **Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard** (**PCI DSS**) is a global data security standard that regulates how entities store, process, and transmit cardholder data (CHD) and/or sensitive authentication data (SAD).
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS includes guidelines regarding components of organizations' technical and operational system that are related to such data.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Cardholder Data refers to information including Primary Account Numbers (PAN), cardholder names, expiration dates, and service codes.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Sensitive authentication data refers to information including "full track data (magnetic-stripe data or equivalent on a chip)," card verification codes, and PINs/PIN blocks.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] This standard is administered by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, and its use is enforced by the major payment card brands.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS was created to improve and streamline the security controls organizations use when handling cardholder data and reduce credit card fraud.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] These organizations, including merchants and service providers, must prove compliance to the PCI DSS through an assessment and validation process.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The payment card brands issue fines and other penalties when merchants or service providers fail to prove compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Before the PCI DSS was launched, payment card information security was handled by the five major payment card brands: Visa, Mastercard, American Express, Discover, and JCB.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The intentions of each were roughly similar: to create an additional level of protection for card issuers by ensuring that merchants meet minimum levels of security when they handle payment cards and related account information.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] As payment card fraud rose in the late 1990s and early 2000s, the major payment card brands felt a growing need to streamline and unify these information security standards.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each program had its own methods and guidance regarding compliance validation, assessments, and requirements.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] To address interoperability problems among the existing standards, the combined effort by these payment card brands resulted in the release of version 1.0 of PCI DSS in December 2004.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The main payment card brands then founded the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council (PCI SSC) and aligned their policies to create the PCI DSS.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS has since been implemented and followed by numerous organizations around the world.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] MasterCard, American Express, Visa, JCB International and Discover Financial Services established the PCI SSC in September 2006 as a global administrative and governing entity that mandates the evolution and development of the PCI DSS.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Independent private organizations can also participate in PCI development as part of the PCI Security Standards Council Participating Organization Program.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] To join that program, organizations must register as a PCI SSC Participating Organization (PO).
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each participating organization joins a SIG (Special Interest Group) and contributes to activities mandated by the group.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS is a living document that is regularly updated by the PCI Security Standards Council.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI SSC releases major version updates, such as version 4.0, approximately every few years.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Minor updates, such as version 4.0.1, are released more frequently and typically add small changes or clarifications.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] When updates are released, organizations have a transition period during which they must become familiar with the new changes and begin ensuring compliance with the current version.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] During the transition period, organizations are only required to be compliant with either the current version or the previous version.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each PCI DSS version has divided these six requirement groups differently, but the twelve requirements have not changed since the inception of the standard.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Testing: The processes and methodologies carried out by the assessor for the confirmation of proper implementation.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Guidance: Explains the purpose of the requirement and the corresponding content, which can assist in its proper definition.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Apply secure configurations to all system components.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Protect cardholder data with strong cryptography during transmission over open, public networks.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Protect all systems and networks from malicious software.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Develop and maintain secure systems and software.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Restrict access to system components and cardholder data by business need to know.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Identify users and authenticate access to system components.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Restrict physical access to cardholder data.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Log and monitor all access to system components and cardholder data.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Test security of systems and networks regularly.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Support information security with organizational policies and programs.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants that store, process, and transmit cardholder data are subject to PCI DSS standards, and thus, must be deemed PCI-compliant.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS framework classifies these entities into merchant levels that determine the type of reporting a business must complete to achieve compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A business' merchant level is determined by its dataset size which refers to the number of transactions a business makes annually.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] An acquirer or payment brand may manually place an organization into a reporting level at its discretion.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Not all payment card brands use all four merchant levels, and each level's transaction volume can vary among payment card brands.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] For instance, Visa only has three merchant levels.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each card issuer maintains a table of compliance levels and a table for service providers.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to the PCI DSS, third-party service providers that store, process, or transmit cardholder data, or have access to customers’ account data are subject to PCI DSS standards.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers can include payment software vendors, software as a service (SaaS), data centers, and other such entities.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers are required to prove PCI DSS compliance through the assessment process.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The type of reporting process a service provider must complete are dependent on the type of service provider.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers are classified into levels which determine the reporting required for compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The payment card brands regularly require both merchants and service providers to demonstrate PCI DSS compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS compliance involves implementing security controls that follow all requirements of the PCI DSS and passing the PCI DSS assessment process to achieve compliance validation.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The major credit card brands enforce PCI DSS compliance by issuing fines for merchants who do not obtain compliance validation.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants and service providers sign business-to-business contracts with payment processors and payment card brands, which outline such fines and fees.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In the event of a merchant's compliance violation, payment card brands issue fines to the acquiring bank who then fines or otherwise penalizes the non-compliant merchant.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Obtaining PCI DSS compliance and navigating the assessment process can be complicated, which is why many businesses often struggle with this.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to Verizon's 2018 Payment Security Report, 47.5% of organizations were not PCI DSS compliant during interim compliance validation.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The number of organizations achieving compliance had been steadily increasing through the early 2010s, but this increase may likely have dropped in recent years.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Compliance validation involves the evaluation and confirmation that the security controls and procedures have been implemented according to the PCI DSS.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Validation occurs through an annual assessment, either by an external entity, or by self-assessment.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Perform the PCI DSS assessment of the environment.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Complete the applicable report for the assessment according to PCI DSS guidance and instructions.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Complete the Attestation of Compliance for Service Providers or Merchants, as applicable, in its entirety.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Submit the applicable PCI SSC documentation and the Attestation of Compliance, along with any other requested documentation to the requesting organization (those that manage compliance programs such as payment brands and acquirers (for merchants), or other requesters (for service providers)).
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A Report on Compliance (ROC) is conducted by a PCI Qualified Security Assessor (QSA) and is intended to provide independent validation of an entity's compliance with the PCI DSS standard.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A completed ROC results in two documents: a ROC Reporting Template populated with detailed explanation of the testing completed, and an Attestation of Compliance (AOC) documenting that a ROC has been completed and the overall conclusion of the ROC.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ) is a validation tool intended for small to medium sized merchants and service providers to assess their own PCI DSS compliance status.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] There are multiple types of SAQ, each with a different length depending on the entity type and payment model used.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each SAQ question has a yes-or-no answer, and any "no" response requires the entity to indicate its future implementation.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] As with ROCs, an attestation of compliance (AOC) based on the SAQ is also completed.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI Security Standards Council maintains a program to certify companies and individuals to perform assessment activities.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A Qualified Security Assessor (QSA) is an individual certified by the PCI Security Standards Council to validate another entity's PCI DSS compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] QSAs must be employed and sponsored by a QSA Company, which also must be certified by the PCI Security Standards Council.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] An Internal Security Assessor (ISA) is an individual who has earned a certificate from the PCI Security Standards Council for their sponsoring organization, and can conduct PCI self-assessments for their organization.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The ISA program was designed to help Level 2 merchants meet Mastercard compliance validation requirements.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] ISA certification empowers an individual to conduct an appraisal of his or her association and propose security solutions and controls for PCI DSS compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] ISAs are in charge of cooperation and participation with QSAs.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Although the PCI DSS must be implemented by all entities which process, store or transmit cardholder data and/or sensitive authentication data or could impact the security of such information, formal validation of PCI DSS compliance is not mandatory for all entities.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Visa and Mastercard require merchants and service providers to be validated according to the PCI DSS; Visa also offers a Technology Innovation Program (TIP), an alternative program which allows qualified merchants to discontinue the annual PCI DSS validation assessment.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants are eligible if they take alternative precautions against fraud, such as the use of EMV or point-to-point encryption.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Issuing banks are not required to undergo PCI DSS validation, although they must secure sensitive data in a PCI DSS-compliant manner.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Acquiring banks must comply with PCI DSS and have their compliance validated with an audit.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In a security breach, any compromised entity which was not PCI DSS-compliant at the time of the breach may be subject to additional penalties (such as fines) from card brands or acquiring banks.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] No governing body/agency requires or enforces PCI DSS compliance, but if any PCI DSS requirements conflict with country, state, or local law, the law will apply.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The European Union’s (EU) General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a legislative standard governing personal data.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] GDPR has similar security control standards as PCI DSS in regards to cardholder data because cardholder data is considered a form of personal data under GDPR.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Hence, for many European organizations, a PCI DSS breach often constitutes a GDPR breach as well, which can result in fines from both major payment card brands and the European Union.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] These GDPR fines can be up to "€20 million or 4% of annual global turnover" (whichever is greatest).
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] While compliance with PCI DSS is not required by federal law in the United States, the laws of some US states refer to PCI DSS directly or make equivalent provisions.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In 2007, Minnesota enacted a law prohibiting the retention of some types of payment-card data more than 48 hours after authorization of a transaction.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Nevada incorporated the standard into state law two years later, requiring compliance by merchants doing business in that state with the current PCI DSS and shielding compliant entities from liability.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The Nevada law also allows merchants to avoid liability by other approved security standards.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In 2010, Washington also incorporated the standard into state law.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Unlike Nevada's law, entities are not required to be PCI DSS-compliant; however, compliant entities are shielded from liability in the event of a data breach.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Legal scholars Edward Morse and Vasant Raval have said that by enshrining PCI DSS compliance in legislation, card networks reallocated the cost of fraud from card issuers to merchants.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The major payment card brands impose fines for non-compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Some business owners, small business owners especially, criticize the PCI DSS system because the payment card brands impose fines on businesses even if no fraud occurs.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Stephen and Theodora "Cissy" McComb, owners of a small restaurant called Cisero's Ristorante and Nightclub in Park City, Utah, were fined for a breach for which two forensics firms could not find evidence.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] They claim the PCI DSS system exists primarily for major card brands to extract profit from these merchant companies rather than ensure cardholder data security.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Proponents of the PCI DSS maintain that the PCI DSS may compel businesses to pay more attention to IT security, even if minimum standards are not enough to eradicate security problems.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Former Visa chief enterprise risk officer Ellen Richey said in 2018, "No compromised entity has yet been found to be in compliance with PCI DSS at the time of a breach".
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] However, a 2008 breach of Heartland Payment Systems (validated as PCI DSS-compliant) resulted in the compromising of more than one hundred million card numbers.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Around that time, Hannaford Brothers and TJX Companies (also validated as PCI DSS-compliant) were similarly breached as a result of the allegedly-coordinated efforts of Albert Gonzalez and two unnamed Russian hackers.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In December 2013, more than forty million Target customer accounts were compromised in a data breach.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Target’s Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer at the time John Mulligan confirmed that Target was certified PCI compliant months before the breach in September 2013.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] News of incidents was widespread and called into question the adequacy of the PCI DSS.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Assessments examine the compliance of merchants and service providers with the PCI DSS at a specific point in time, frequently using sampling to allow compliance to be demonstrated with representative systems and processes.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] It is the responsibility of the merchant and service provider to achieve, demonstrate, and maintain compliance throughout the annual validation-and-assessment cycle across all systems and processes.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A breakdown in merchant and service-provider compliance with the written standard may have been responsible for the breaches; Hannaford Brothers received its PCI DSS compliance validation one day after it had been made aware of a two-month-long compromise of its internal systems.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Compliance validation is required only for level 1 to 3 merchants and may be optional for Level 4, depending on the card brand and acquirer.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to Visa's compliance validation details for merchants, level-4 merchant compliance-validation requirements ("Merchants processing less than 20,000 Visa e-commerce transactions annually and all other merchants processing up to 1 million Visa transactions annually") are set by the acquirer.
[src:tokenization-data/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Over 80 percent of payment-card compromises between 2005 and 2007 affected level-4 merchants, who handled 32 percent of all such transactions.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] A **payment card number**, **primary account number** (**PAN**), or simply a **card number**, is the card identifier found on payment cards, such as credit cards and debit cards, as well as stored-value cards, gift cards and other similar cards.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] In some situations the card number is referred to as a **bank card number**.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The card number is primarily a card identifier and may not directly identify the bank account number(s) to which the card is/are linked by the issuing entity.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The card number prefix identifies the issuer of the card, and the digits that follow are used by the issuing entity to identify the cardholder as a customer and which is then associated by the issuing entity with the customer's designated bank accounts.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] In the case of stored-value type cards, the association with a particular customer is only made if the prepaid card is reloadable.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Card numbers are allocated in accordance with ISO/IEC 7812.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The card number is typically embossed on the front of a payment card, and is encoded on the magnetic stripe and chip, but may also be imprinted on the back of the card.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The payment card number differs from the Business Identifier Code (BIC/ISO 9362, a normalized code—also known as Business Identifier Code, Bank International Code or SWIFT code).
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] It also differs from Universal Payment Identification Code, another identifier for a bank account in the United States.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Payment card numbers are composed of 8 to 19 digits, The leading six or eight digits are the **issuer identification number** (**IIN**) sometimes referred to as the **bank identification number** (**BIN**).
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The remaining numbers, except the last digit, are the individual account identification number.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] IINs and PANs have a certain level of internal structure and share a common numbering scheme set by ISO/IEC 7812.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The first six or eight digits of a card number (including the initial MII digit) are known as the issuer identification number (IIN).
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] These identify the card issuing institution that issued the card to the card holder.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The rest of the number is allocated by the card issuer.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The card number's *length* is its number of digits.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Many card issuers print the entire IIN and account number on their card.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] In some circumstances, the issuer identification number (IIN) or bank identification number (BIN) may not be licensed directly from the issuing network (such as Mastercard or Visa).
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Obtaining a BIN/IIN number can be costly, time-consuming and demand intensive operational burdens on in-house regulatory and compliance teams.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] For this reason, some new card programs may use a 'BIN sponsor', in which case the IIN/BIN number is effectively sub-licensed from a scheme regulated entity.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] This is known as BIN sponsorship, and is a popular way for financial institutions to fast-track access to market.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] In the United States, IINs are also used in NCPDP pharmacy claims to identify processors, and are printed on all pharmacy insurance cards.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] IINs are the primary routing mechanism for real-time claims.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The ISO Register of Issuer Identification Numbers database is managed by the American Bankers Association.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] ABA is the Registration Authority for this standard and is responsible for allocating IINs to issuers.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Online merchants may use IIN lookups to help validate transactions.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] For example, if a card's IIN indicates a bank in one country, while the customer's billing address is in another, the transaction may call for extra scrutiny.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] On 8 November 2004, Mastercard and Diners Club formed an alliance.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Diners Club cards issued in Canada and the United States start with 54 or 55 and are treated as Mastercards worldwide.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] International cards use the 36 prefix and are treated as Mastercards in Canada and the United States, but are treated as Diners Club cards elsewhere.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Diners Club International's website makes no reference to old 38 prefix numbers, and they can be presumed reissued under the 55 or 36 IIN prefix.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Effective 16 October 2009, Diners Club cards beginning with 30, 36, 38 or 39 have been processed by Discover Card.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] On 3 November 2014, Mastercard announced that they were introducing a new series of BIN ranges that begin with a "2" (222100–272099).
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The "2" series BINs will be processed the same as the "51–55" series BINs are today.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] On 23 July 2014 JSC NSPK was established in the Russian Federation.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The joint stock company National System of Payment Cards (NSPK) is the operator of the Mir National Payment System.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] The main initiatives of NSPK are to create the national payment system infrastructure and to issue a national payment card, Mir.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Effective 1 October 2006, Discover began using the entire 65 prefix, not just 650.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Also, similar to the Mastercard/Diners agreement, China UnionPay cards are now treated as Discover cards and accepted on the Discover network.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] While the vast majority of Visa's account ranges describe 16 digit card numbers there are still a few account ranges (forty as of 11 December 2013) dedicated to 13 digit PANs and several (439 as of 11 December2013) account ranges where the issuer can mix 13 and 16 digit card numbers.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Visa's VPay brand can specify PAN lengths from 13 to 19 digits and so card numbers of more than 16 digits are now being seen.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] Switch was re-branded as Maestro in mid-2007.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] In 2011, UK domestic Maestro (formerly Switch) was aligned with the standard international Maestro proposition with the retention of a few residual country specific rules.
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] EMV Certification requires acceptance of a 19-digit Visa card (ADVT 6.1.1 Test Case 2) and Discover Card (E2E Test Plan v1.3, Test Case 06).
[src:tokenization-data/primary-account-number] To reduce the risk of credit card fraud, various techniques are used to prevent the dissemination of bank card numbers.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization (or pseudonymisation, the spelling under European guidelines) is one way to comply with the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) demands for secure data storage of personal information.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data can be restored to its original state with the addition of information which allows individuals to be re-identified.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] In contrast, anonymization is intended to prevent re-identification of individuals within the dataset.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] The European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) on 9 December 2021 highlighted pseudonymization as the top technical supplementary measure for Schrems II compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Less than two weeks later, the EU Commission highlighted pseudonymization as an essential element of the equivalency decision for South Korea, which is the status that was lost by the United States under the Schrems II ruling by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU).
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Protects against unauthorized re-identification via the mosaic effect by generating high entropy (uncertainty) levels by dynamically assigning different tokens at different times for various purposes.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Before the Schrems II ruling, pseudonymization was a technique used by security experts or government officials to hide personally identifiable information to maintain data structure and privacy of information.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Some common examples of sensitive information include postal code, location of individuals, names of individuals, race and gender, etc.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] After the Schrems II ruling, GDPR-compliant pseudonymization must satisfy the above-noted elements as an "outcome" versus merely a technique.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] The choice of which data fields are to be pseudonymized is partly subjective.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Less selective fields, such as birth date or postal code are often also included because they are usually available from other sources and therefore make a record easier to identify.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Pseudonymizing these less identifying fields removes most of their analytic value and is therefore normally accompanied by the introduction of new derived and less identifying forms, such as year of birth or a larger postal code region.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Data fields that are less identifying, such as date of attendance, are usually not pseudonymized.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] This is because too much statistical utility is lost in doing so, not because the data cannot be identified.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] For example, given prior knowledge of a few attendance dates it is easy to identify someone's data in a pseudonymized dataset by selecting only those people with that pattern of dates.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] This is an example of an inference attack.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] The weakness of pre-GDPR pseudonymized data to inference attacks is commonly overlooked.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] A famous example is the AOL search data scandal.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] The pseudonym allows tracking back of data to its origins, which distinguishes pseudonymization from anonymization, where all person-related data that could allow backtracking has been purged.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization is an issue in, for example, patient-related data that has to be passed on securely between clinical centers.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] The application of pseudonymization to e-health intends to preserve the patient's privacy and data confidentiality.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] It allows primary use of medical records by authorized health care providers and privacy preserving secondary use by researchers.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] In the US, HIPAA provides guidelines on how health care data must be handled and data de-identification or pseudonymization is one way to simplify HIPAA compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] However, plain pseudonymization for privacy preservation often reaches its limits when genetic data are involved (see also genetic privacy).
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Due to the identifying nature of genetic data, depersonalization is often not sufficient to hide the corresponding person.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Potential solutions are the combination of pseudonymization with fragmentation and encryption.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Effective as of May 25, 2018, the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) defines pseudonymization for the very first time at the EU level in Article 4(5).
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Under Article 4(5) definitional requirements, data is pseudonymized if it cannot be attributed to a specific data subject without the use of separately kept "additional information".
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data embodies the state of the art in Data Protection by Design and by Default because it requires protection of both direct and indirect identifiers (not just direct).
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Because access to separately kept "additional information" is required for re-identification, attribution of data to a specific data subject can be limited by the controller to support lawful purposes only.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] "...implement appropriate technical and organizational measures for ensuring that, by default, only personal data which are necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] That obligation applies to the amount of personal data collected, the extent of their processing, the period of their storage and their accessibility.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] A central core of Data Protection by Design and by Default under GDPR Article 25 is enforcement of technology controls that support appropriate uses and the ability to keep promises.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] This trust cannot be maintained using outdated approaches to data protection.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization, as newly defined under the GDPR, is a means of helping to achieve Data Protection by Design and by Default to earn and maintain trust and more effectively serve businesses, researchers, healthcare providers, and everyone who relies on the integrity of data.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] GDPR-compliant pseudonymization not only enables greater privacy-respectful use of data in the "big data" world of data sharing and combining, but it also enables data controllers and processors to reap explicit benefits under the GDPR for correctly pseudonymized data.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Article 9(2)(j) with regard to overcoming the general prohibition on processing Article 9(1) special categories of personal data.
[src:tokenization-data/pseudonymization] Under Article 20(1), data controllers using Legitimate Interest processing are not subject to the right of portability, which applies only to consent-based processing.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system must be secured and validated using security best practices applicable to sensitive data protection, secure storage, audit, authentication and authorization.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system provides data processing applications with the authority and interfaces to request tokens, or detokenize back to sensitive data.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The security and risk reduction benefits of tokenization require that the tokenization system is logically isolated and segmented from data processing systems and applications that previously processed or stored sensitive data replaced by tokens.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Only the tokenization system can tokenize data to create tokens, or detokenize back to redeem sensitive data under strict security controls.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The token generation method must be proven to have the property that there is no feasible means through direct attack, cryptanalysis, side channel analysis, token mapping table exposure or brute force techniques to reverse tokens back to live data.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Replacing live data with tokens in systems is intended to minimize exposure of sensitive data to those applications, stores, people and processes, reducing risk of compromise or accidental exposure and unauthorized access to sensitive data.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Applications can operate using tokens instead of live data, with the exception of a small number of trusted applications explicitly permitted to detokenize when strictly necessary for an approved business purpose.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems may be operated in-house within a secure isolated segment of the data center, or as a service from a secure service provider.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization may be used to safeguard sensitive data involving, for example, bank accounts, financial statements, medical records, criminal records, driver's licenses, loan applications, stock trades, voter registrations, and other types of personally identifiable information (PII).
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is often used in credit card processing.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council defines tokenization as "a process by which the primary account number (PAN) is replaced with a surrogate value called a token.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] A PAN may be linked to a reference number through the tokenization process.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In this case, the merchant simply has to retain the token and a reliable third party controls the relationship and holds the PAN.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The token may be created independently of the PAN, or the PAN can be used as part of the data input to the tokenization technique.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The communication between the merchant and the third-party supplier must be secure to prevent an attacker from intercepting to gain the PAN and the token.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] De-tokenization is the reverse process of redeeming a token for its associated PAN value.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The security of an individual token relies predominantly on the infeasibility of determining the original PAN knowing only the surrogate value".
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The choice of tokenization as an alternative to other techniques such as encryption will depend on varying regulatory requirements, interpretation, and acceptance by respective auditing or assessment entities.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This is in addition to any technical, architectural or operational constraint that tokenization imposes in practical use.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The concept of tokenization, as adopted by the industry today, has existed since the first currency systems emerged centuries ago as a means to reduce risk in handling high value financial instruments by replacing them with surrogate equivalents.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In the physical world, coin tokens have a long history of use replacing the financial instrument of minted coins and banknotes.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In more recent history, subway tokens and casino chips found adoption for their respective systems to replace physical currency and cash handling risks such as theft.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Exonumia and scrip are terms synonymous with such tokens.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In the digital world, similar substitution techniques have been used since the 1970s as a means to isolate real data elements from exposure to other data systems.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In databases for example, surrogate key values have been used since 1976 to isolate data associated with the internal mechanisms of databases and their external equivalents for a variety of uses in data processing.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] More recently, these concepts have been extended to consider this isolation tactic to provide a security mechanism for the purposes of data protection.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In the payment card industry, tokenization is one means of protecting sensitive cardholder data in order to comply with industry standards and government regulations.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization was applied to payment card data by Shift4 Corporation and released to the public during an industry Security Summit in Las Vegas, Nevada in 2005.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The technology is meant to prevent the theft of the credit card information in storage.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Shift4 defines tokenization as: "The concept of using a non-decryptable piece of data to represent, by reference, sensitive or secret data.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] To protect data over its full lifecycle, tokenization is often combined with end-to-end encryption to secure data in transit to the tokenization system or service, with a token replacing the original data on return.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] For example, to avoid the risks of malware stealing data from low-trust systems such as point of sale (POS) systems, as in the Target breach of 2013, cardholder data encryption must take place prior to card data entering the POS and not after.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also specified end-to-end encryption (certified point-to-point encryption—P2PE) for various service implementations in various PCI Council Point-to-point Encryption documents.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems share several components according to established standards.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Token mapping – this is the process of assigning the created token value to its original value.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] To enable permitted look-ups of the original value using the token as the index, a secure cross-reference database must be constructed.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Token data store – this is a central repository for the token mapping process that holds the original sensitive values and their related token values.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Sensitive data and token values must be securely kept in an encrypted format.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Strong key management procedures are required for sensitive data encryption on token data stores.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization and "classic" encryption effectively protect data if implemented properly, and a computer security system may use both.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] While similar in certain regards, tokenization and classic encryption differ in a few key aspects.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Both are cryptographic data security methods and they essentially have the same function, however they do so with differing processes and have different effects on the data they are protecting.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes without altering the type or length of data.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This is an important distinction from encryption because changes in data length and type can render information unreadable in intermediate systems such as databases.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenized data can still be processed by legacy systems which makes tokenization more flexible than classic encryption.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In many situations, the encryption process is a constant consumer of processing power, hence such a system needs significant expenditures in specialized hardware and software.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Another difference is that tokens require significantly less computational resources to process.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] With tokenization, specific data is kept fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This allows tokenized data to be processed more quickly and reduces the strain on system resources.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This can be a key advantage in systems that rely on high performance.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In comparison to encryption, tokenization technologies reduce time, expense, and administrative effort while enabling teamwork and communication.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] There are many ways that tokens can be classified.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] However, there is currently no unified classification.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be single or multi-use, cryptographic or non-cryptographic, reversible or irreversible, authenticable or non-authenticable, and various combinations thereof.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In the context of payments, the difference between high and low value tokens plays a significant role.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] High-value tokens (HVT) serve as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions and are used as an instrument for completing a payment transaction.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In order to function, they must look like actual PANs.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Multiple HVT can map back to a single PAN and a single physical credit card without the owner being aware of it.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Additionally, HVT can be limited to certain networks and/or merchants whereas PANs cannot.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] HVT can also be bound to specific devices so that anomalies between token use, physical devices, and geographic locations can be flagged as potentially fraudulent.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] HVT blocking enhances efficiency by reducing computational costs while maintaining accuracy and reducing record linkage as it reduces the number of records that are compared.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Low-value tokens (LVT) also act as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions, however they serve a different purpose.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] LVT cannot be used by themselves to complete a payment transaction.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In order for an LVT to function, it must be possible to match it back to the actual PAN it represents, albeit only in a tightly controlled fashion.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Using tokens to protect PANs becomes ineffectual if a tokenization system is breached, therefore securing the tokenization system itself is extremely important.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] First generation tokenization systems use a database to map from live data to surrogate substitute tokens and back.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This requires the storage, management, and continuous backup for every new transaction added to the token database to avoid data loss.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Another problem is ensuring consistency across data centers, requiring continuous synchronization of token databases.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Significant consistency, availability and performance trade-offs, per the CAP theorem, are unavoidable with this approach.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This overhead adds complexity to real-time transaction processing to avoid data loss and to assure data integrity across data centers, and also limits scale.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Storing all sensitive data in one service creates an attractive target for attack and compromise, and introduces privacy and legal risk in the aggregation of data Internet privacy, particularly in the EU.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Another limitation of tokenization technologies is measuring the level of security for a given solution through independent validation.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] With the lack of standards, the latter is critical to establish the strength of tokenization offered when tokens are used for regulatory compliance.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The method of generating tokens may also have limitations from a security perspective.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] With concerns about security and attacks to random number generators, which are a common choice for the generation of tokens and token mapping tables, scrutiny must be applied to ensure proven and validated methods are used versus arbitrary design.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Random-number generators have limitations in terms of speed, entropy, seeding and bias, and security properties must be carefully analysed and measured to avoid predictability and compromise.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Stateless tokenization allows live data elements to be mapped to surrogate values randomly, without relying on a database, while maintaining the isolation properties of tokenization.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] November 2014, American Express released its token service which meets the EMV tokenization standard.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Other notable examples of tokenization-based payment systems, according to the EMVCo standard, include Google Wallet, Apple Pay, Samsung Pay, Microsoft Wallet, Fitbit Pay and Garmin Pay.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Visa uses tokenization techniques to provide a secure online and mobile shopping.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Using blockchain, as opposed to relying on trusted third parties, it is possible to run highly accessible, tamper-resistant databases for transactions.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] With help of blockchain, tokenization is the process of converting the value of a tangible or intangible asset into a token that can be exchanged on the network.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This enables the tokenization of conventional financial assets, for instance, by transforming rights into a digital token backed by the asset itself using blockchain technology.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Besides that, tokenization enables the simple and efficient compartmentalization and management of data across multiple users.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Individual tokens created through tokenization can be used to split ownership and partially resell an asset.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Consequently, only entities with the appropriate token can access the data.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Numerous blockchain companies support asset tokenization.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In 2019, eToro acquired Firmo and renamed as eToroX.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Through its Token Management Suite, which is backed by USD-pegged stablecoins, eToroX enables asset tokenization.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization of equity is facilitated by STOKR, a platform that links investors with small and medium-sized businesses.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokens issued through the STOKR platform are legally recognized as transferable securities under European Union capital market regulations.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Breakers enable tokenization of intellectual property, allowing content creators to issue their own digital tokens.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be distributed to a variety of project participants.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Without intermediaries or governing body, content creators can integrate reward-sharing features into the token.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Building an alternate payments system requires a number of entities working together in order to deliver near field communication (NFC) or other technology based payment services to the end users.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] One of the issues is the interoperability between the players and to resolve this issue the role of trusted service manager (TSM) is proposed to establish a technical link between mobile network operators (MNO) and providers of services, so that these entities can work together.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can play a role in mediating such services.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization as a security strategy lies in the ability to replace a real card number with a surrogate (target removal) and the subsequent limitations placed on the surrogate card number (risk reduction).
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] If the surrogate value can be used in an unlimited fashion or even in a broadly applicable manner, the token value gains as much value as the real credit card number.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In these cases, the token may be secured by a second dynamic token that is unique for each transaction and also associated to a specific payment card.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Example of dynamic, transaction-specific tokens include cryptograms used in the EMV (Europay, Mastercard, and Visa) specification.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, an industry-wide set of guidelines that must be met by any organization that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data, mandates that credit card data must be protected when stored.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization, as applied to payment card data, is often implemented to meet this mandate, replacing credit card and automated clearing house (ACH) numbers in some systems with a random value or string of characters.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be formatted in a variety of ways.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Some token service providers or tokenization products generate the surrogate values in such a way as to match the format of the original sensitive data.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In the case of payment card data, a token might be the same length as a primary account number (bank card number) and contain elements of the original data such as the last four digits of the card number.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] When a payment card authorization request is made to verify the legitimacy of a transaction, a token might be returned to the merchant instead of the card number, along with the authorization code for the transaction.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The token is stored in the receiving system while the actual cardholder data is mapped to the token in a secure tokenization system.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Storage of tokens and payment card data must comply with current PCI standards, including the use of strong cryptography.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is currently in standards definition in ANSI X9 as X9.119 Part 2.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] X9 is responsible for the industry standards for financial cryptography and data protection including payment card PIN management, credit and debit card encryption and related technologies and processes.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also stated support for tokenization in reducing risk in data breaches, when combined with other technologies such as Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) and assessments of compliance to PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Visa Inc. released Visa Tokenization Best Practices for tokenization uses in credit and debit card handling applications and services.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] In March 2014, EMVCo LLC released its first payment tokenization specification for EMV.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] PCI DSS is the most frequently utilized standard for Tokenization systems used by payment industry players.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can render it more difficult for attackers to gain access to sensitive data outside of the tokenization system or service.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Implementation of tokenization may simplify the requirements of the PCI DSS, as systems that no longer store or process sensitive data may have a reduction of applicable controls required by the PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] This validation is particularly important in tokenization, as the tokens are shared externally in general use and thus exposed in high risk, low trust environments.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] The infeasibility of reversing a token or set of tokens to a live sensitive data must be established using industry accepted measurements and proofs by appropriate experts independent of the service or solution provider.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Not all organizational data can be tokenized, and needs to be examined and filtered.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] When databases are utilized on a large scale, they expand exponentially, causing the search process to take longer, restricting system performance, and increasing backup processes.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] A database that links sensitive information to tokens is called a vault.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] With the addition of new data, the vault's maintenance workload increases significantly.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] For ensuring database consistency, token databases need to be continuously synchronized.
[src:tokenization-data/tokenization-data-security] Apart from that, secure communication channels must be built between sensitive data and the vault so that data is not compromised on the way to or from storage.
